If an xwork plugin action can't be instantiated, for whatever reason, the ConfluencePluginObjectFatory passes all exceptions through to xwork.  Xwork then catches the exception, and throws an IllegalArgumentException, with no reference to the original exception, not even passing it as the cause:

{noformat}
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: Method 'doDefault()' is not defined in action 'class com.atlassian.studio.confluence.themes.sidebar.ConfigureSidebarAction'
{noformat}

There are no errors in the logs to indicate that the cause is that the plugin class couldn't be instantiated, and certainly nothing saying why it can't be instantiated.  I suggest that the ConfluencePluginObjectFactory catches and logs any exceptions thrown when instantiating the plugin action.

John Baker reported this bug in CSP-30220:
{quote}
While developing a plugin for Confluence, I noticed a bug in the DownloadGatekeeper object.  I have registered a  path using allowAnonymousAccess, and this uses the string %anon% as part of a key:
{code}
    private String generateKey(String userName, String path)
    {
        StringBuffer key = new StringBuffer();
        key.append(userName != null ? userName : "%anon%");
        key.append("|");
        key.append(path);
        return key.toString();
    }
{code}
However, when a request is made to isAccessPermitted, and a user is logged in, the code only checks the current user and not anonymous:
{code}
    public boolean isAccessPermitted(String path, String userName)
    {
        runCheck();

        boolean result = permittedDownloads.containsKey(generateKey(userName, path));
        if (log.isDebugEnabled())
            log.debug("Permission check for user '" + userName + "' and path '" + path + "' returned: " + result);

        return result;
    }
{code}
The function should look something like:
{code}
    public boolean isAccessPermitted(String path, String userName)
    {
        runCheck();

        boolean result = permittedDownloads.containsKey(generateKey(userName, path));
        if (!result && userName != null) result = permittedDownloads.containsKey(generateKey("%anon%", path));
        if (log.isDebugEnabled())
            log.debug("Permission check for user '" + userName + "' and path '" + path + "' returned: " + result);

        return result;
    }
{code}
Therefore, when a user is logged in, and a resource has been marked anonymous (available to all), only the user who created the resource can download it.  
{quote}

{quote}
The code is broken because the API documentation clearly states that marking a path as anonyous allows access to both anonymous and logged in users, and that's not what the code does.  It gives access to annoymous users only, because the isAccessPermitted will only return true for an anonymous user.
 :
In my scenerio, I'm modifying the Graphviz and Latex plugins to cache the images produced by the external process.  I'm generating an image and adding the path as anonymous so all users can view that image, yet as a result, only anonymous users can view the image.
{quote}

